body:
In `Editor > Color Scheme > Dart` there should be a specific color for when a required parameter is missing. This would make it much easier to tell the problem, improving usability.

At the moment this is just marked as any other error.

comment_data.body: @stevemessick Dart plugin uses Analysis Server for code highlighting. A set of available highlighting types is specified in the [HighlightRegionType](https://htmlpreview.github.io/?https://github.com/dart-lang/sdk/blob/master/pkg/analysis_server/doc/api.html#type_HighlightRegionType) class. We can't support any highlighting type not listed there.
This issue was moved by [stevemessick](https://github.com/stevemessick) to [dart-lang/sdk#45809](https://github.com/dart-lang/sdk/issues/45809).

@stevemessick @alexander-doroshko According to @bwilkerson we already can support the difference in highlighting. In that case, can this issue be reopened here?

This is my top highlighting issue with the IntelliJ plugin. It actually hurts usability that the highlighting does not help us see this NNBD problems. If we could see a different color it would just be a lot faster/easier to fix this very common mistakes in the code.
I think this should be done by Dart plugin, but I'm re-opening this anyway.

Sorry, my comment about HighlightRegionType was not accurate. Thanks Brian for the correct info in https://github.com/dart-lang/sdk/issues/45809#issuecomment-825699286.

That's true that the IDE highlights all errors in a similar way (as well as all warnings, and all hints), and there's no exception for "missing required parameter" error. 

It's theoretically possible to provide separate highlighting configuration for specific errors/warnings/hints but at this point this seems like an overdesign to me. There should be very strong reasons to treat some errors as more specific than the others. I'm not aware of such reasons.

Meanwhile, sorting by name in the Dart Analysis view should help with searching for errors of a specific type across the whole project.

> There should be very strong reasons to treat some errors as more specific than the others. 
> I'm not aware of such reasons.

To be honest I have never felt any need to differentiate errors like this before, but I do feel the need with these kinds of errors. These NNBD errors are now the most common that happen just as you type. I'd say they are now more than 50% of the errors I get when I type. If you know right away if they are NNBD related, it makes it much easier to just fix them on the spot. Sorting by name in the Dart Analysis doesn't help, since the goal is to see right away the type of error as you type. Most of the time you just need to include a `?` or a `!` and that's easier to do as you type or paste something, since you have all the code context in mind. 

But if that's close to impossible to implement, ok, we can live without it. Thanks.
@InMatrix The topic of showing some errors differently than others sounds like a candidate for a UXR study. See the previous two comments for context.
